{
  "texts": [
    "But as our specific character resides precisely in this, that, born almost without instinct, we are raised to manhood only by lifelong practice, on which both the perfectibility as well as by its inherited understanding of the world (Kuhn 1997; Zamora Bonilla 2006).",
    "As noted above, specific technological forms may generate a flood of information that inhibit the communication of information (Pfister 2011).",
    "Finally, one of the challenges presented by the 'epistemic horizon' (as of that of an 'event horizon' 20) is that we cannot observe directly its limits.",
    "For example, the presence of an event our current model takes to be very rare (e.g.a \"20-sigma\" event) can suggest our current model is incorrect, but in the absence of such a rare event, we cannot know if the current tails of knowledge are correct or too thin (Taleb 2007).",
    "These considerations suggest the concern of generational knowledge collapse is plausible and an unbounded optimism in the ability of rational actors to update on the value of tail knowledge may be shortsighted."
  ]
}